<subSubSection id="C31770F2FF95884DFF6167CFBCDBA284" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BB22379FF95884DFF6167CFBAA4A4E9" blockId="7.[192,1152,658,685]" box="[192,1152,658,685]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis id="B979FF6BFF95884DFF6167CFBF60A4E9" bold="true" box="[192,324,658,684]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is chosen to indicate the similarity to 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D58FAFF95884DFC1467CFBAA4A4E9" authority="Wood." authorityName="Wood." box="[949,1152,658,685]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Corthylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosus">
<emphasis id="B979FF6BFF95884DFC1467CFBDE3A4E9" box="[949,967,658,684]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B979FF6BFF95884DFC7267CEBA0AA4E9" box="[979,1070,659,684]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">spinosus</emphasis>
Wood.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB22379FF95884DFF61678BBACAA4B6" blockId="7.[192,1262,726,790]" box="[192,1262,726,755]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis id="B979FF6BFF95884DFF61678BBACAA4B6" bold="true" box="[192,1262,726,755]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Species with third declivital interstriae serrate and displaced mesally towards suture</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB22379FF95884DFF6167A6BFECA550" blockId="7.[192,1262,726,790]" box="[192,456,763,790]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">
<figureCitation id="13363FFCFF95884DFF6167A6BF18A553" box="[192,316,763,790]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="6.[192,268,1665,1691]" captionTargetBox="[306,1327,213,1632]" captionTargetId="figure-82@6.[306,1327,213,1634]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 3. Species of Corthylus with acute spines on declivity or with interstriae 3 curved and serrate (1 of 2). A, B) C. spinosulus, new species, holotype. C–D) C. spinosus Wood, holotype. E, F) C. spinipennis Wood, holotype. G, H) C. senticosus Wood, holotype. Photographs A–B by the author, C–H by S.M. Smith (Copyright National Museum of Natural History, Smithsonian Institution, Washington, D.C., published by permission)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4564897" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4564897/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Fig. 3 G, H</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="13363FFCFF95884DFEE667A6BFA0A550" box="[327,388,763,789]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="8.[192,268,1672,1698]" captionTargetBox="[305,1326,213,1641]" captionTargetId="figure-10@8.[305,1326,213,1641]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 4. Species of Corthylus with acute spines on declivity or with interstriae 3 curved and serrate (2 of 2). A, B) C. cristatus new species, holotype. C, D) C. cristatulus new species, holotype. E, F) C. granulocristatus new species, holotype. G, H) C. poblanus new species, holotype. All photographs by the author." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4564899" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4564899/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
A–H.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB22379FF95884DFF61667BBCDBA284" blockId="7.[191,1441,806,1218]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">
The following four species have the third declivital interstriae strongly elevated with prominent granules giving a serrate appearance. These interstriae are in the “normal” position at the base and apex of the declivity but strongly displaced mesally towards the elytral juncture in the center of the declivity. The degree of displacement is so pronounced in several of these species that the elevation appears to be on the second interstriae (
<figureCitation id="13363FFCFF95884DFB6F66D2BB2BA5EC" box="[1230,1295,911,937]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="8.[192,268,1672,1698]" captionTargetBox="[305,1326,213,1641]" captionTargetId="figure-10@8.[305,1326,213,1641]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 4. Species of Corthylus with acute spines on declivity or with interstriae 3 curved and serrate (2 of 2). A, B) C. cristatus new species, holotype. C, D) C. cristatulus new species, holotype. E, F) C. granulocristatus new species, holotype. G, H) C. poblanus new species, holotype. All photographs by the author." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4564899" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4564899/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
, A–F). These species would key out to couplet 
<quantity id="4CF58E9CFF95884DFD9366EFBC4FA589" box="[562,619,946,972]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" unit="in" value="40.0">40 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation id="EF9C5E88FF95884DFDD366EFBD24A589" author="Wood SL" box="[626,768,946,972]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 1356" refId="ref9695" refString="Wood SL. 1982. The bark and ambrosia beetles of North and Central America (Coleoptera: Scolytidae), a taxonomic monograph. Great Basin Naturalist Memoirs 6: 1 - 1356." type="journal article" year="1982">Wood’s 1982</bibRefCitation>
key but would not go further. They would key to couplet 
<quantity id="4CF58E9CFF95884DFA2466EFBEFCA5AA" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2098" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" unit="in" value="87.0">87 in</quantity>
his 2007 key but would not progress beyond this point. The declivity in these species resembles that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D58FAFF95884DFAE4668BBF67A257" authority="Wood" authorityName="Wood" authorityYear="1986" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Corthylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senticosus">
<emphasis id="B979FF6BFF95884DFAE4668BBB73A5B5" box="[1349,1367,982,1008]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B979FF6BFF95884DFAC5668BBEDDA257" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">senticosus</emphasis>
Wood
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="13363FFCFF95884DFEF366A5BFB7A257" box="[338,403,1016,1042]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="6.[192,268,1665,1691]" captionTargetBox="[306,1327,213,1632]" captionTargetId="figure-82@6.[306,1327,213,1634]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 3. Species of Corthylus with acute spines on declivity or with interstriae 3 curved and serrate (1 of 2). A, B) C. spinosulus, new species, holotype. C–D) C. spinosus Wood, holotype. E, F) C. spinipennis Wood, holotype. G, H) C. senticosus Wood, holotype. Photographs A–B by the author, C–H by S.M. Smith (Copyright National Museum of Natural History, Smithsonian Institution, Washington, D.C., published by permission)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4564897" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4564897/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
, G, H), but the female frons is totally different and the depth and size of the punctures on the disc of the declivity is much less pronounced. In the three of the four species described here the female frons is convex with no pubescence or surface features in the lower portion and with short, straight setae along the upper and lateral margins; in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D58FAFF95884DFE60613FBC6FA23E" authorityName="Wood" authorityYear="1986" box="[449,587,1122,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Corthylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senticosus">
<emphasis id="B979FF6BFF95884DFE60613FBFF7A239" box="[449,467,1122,1148]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B979FF6BFF95884DFE7E613FBC6FA23E" box="[479,587,1122,1147]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">senticosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
there are large, yellow spongy areas occupying most of the frontal concavity, a prominent elevation above the epistoma, and a recurved margin of long hairs along the vertical margin (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9C5E88FF95884DFAF561D9BF0AA287" author="Wood SL" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" pagination="265 - 273" refId="ref9730" refString="Wood SL. 1986. New synonymy and new species of American bark beetles (Coleoptera: Scolytidae), Part XI. Great Basin Naturalist 46 (2): 265 - 273." type="journal article" year="1986">Wood, 1986: 271</bibRefCitation>
). The female of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D58FAFF95884DFE7E61F5BC44A284" authorityName="Atkinson" authorityYear="2020" box="[479,608,1191,1218]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Corthylus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="poblanus">
<emphasis id="B979FF6BFF95884DFE7E61F5BFD5A287" box="[479,497,1192,1218]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B979FF6BFF95884DFE5C61FABC44A284" box="[509,608,1191,1217]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">poblanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
